Discussion of Case~B:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item The comparator at $v_6$ detects the first mismatch at index 2 (LSB); eq_out goes to $0$ and mismatch flag becomes $1$ which persists to the rightmost end. Thus EqAccept=0 and NeqAccept=1.
\item By the seam table, when the local comparator end exposes Neq=1 the seam is allowed to carry $\PAD$; hence both left and right seam edges carry $\PAD$ as shown. Note that $\CAP$ is forbidden because Eq=0.
\item Selected(2)=1 and SelectedSgn=$-$ are consistent with S2=$\Otwo$ and with the RUN sgn[2]=$-$.
\item Barriers are present and no witness tokens cross them.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Where illegal attempts get stuck}
We indicate two examples of illegal attempts and show the local point of rejection (a radius--1 violation):
\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
\item Attempt to place $\CAP$ in Case~B despite Neq (i.e. an adversary tries to put $\CAP$ at $(v_6,v_7)$ while the comparator shows Neq=1): this violates the left seam local rule which requires Eq=1 for $\CAP$. The local radius--1 neighbourhood of nodes $v_6,v_7$ and the adjacent comparator tile now shows (CertTrack=$\CAP$, Eq=0) which is not in the allowed list. Hence the configuration is rejected locally at the seam edge.
\item Attempt to place $\CAP$ in Case~A but with sign mismatch: suppose an adversary attempted to put $\CAP$ at $(v_7,v_8)$ but altered S1 to $\VF$ while RUN sgn[1]=$+$ (so SelectedSgn=$+$). The right seam local rule requires SelectedSgn to equal the S1 sign (mapping $\VT\mapsto+$, $\VF\mapsto-$). The neighbourhood $(S1=\VF, SelectedSgn=+)$ violates the local sign-match requirement; hence the tile at $v_7$ adjacent to the seam fails the radius--1 check and is rejected.
\end{enumerate}
These two points demonstrate concretely how CAP/PAD leakage or sign-mismatch CAPs are prevented by purely local checks.

\section{Summary and remarks}
We have produced:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item explicit seam adjacency tables that implement the invariants required by the verifier notes (no $\botSym$ when Offer, CertStart default, CAP only on Eq+sign match, PAD only on Neq, no CAP/PAD leakage);
\item unified S-palettes $\mathcal S_1$ and $\mathcal S_2$;
\item per-bit comparator tiles and HotRID$\leftrightarrow$RIDbit pointer-integrity local rules, RUN exposure and Selected gating, and a short inductive proof that Eq and Neq cannot both accept;
\item barrier tokens and local rules forbidding witness/cursor crossing, with an F2 locality argument showing repetition of modules separated by barriers produces independent, well-formed modules;
\item an optional radius--1 input-forwarding track for activation; and
\item a concrete $B=2$ patch (12 nodes) with an ON and an OFF instance, listed with exact tokens and explicit local failure points for illegal attempts.
\end{itemize}

Everything in this document is stated as radius--1 local rules (allowed adjacency/triple patterns) and short proofs that are purely local or inductive over the bit-chain, hence fully rigorous within the tiling/local-rule model. If you would like these tables translated into canonical Wang-tile listing (one tile per allowed radius--1 neighbourhood), or into an explicit finite-state automaton enumerating the allowed labels on each site, I can produce that next (for example: enumerate all allowed triples per seam edge and all allowed per-bit comparator neighbourhood tiles as a machine-readable table).

